
Tracked assets are a builder policy over frontend-rendered path usages.

The frontend records semantic path facts while rendering paths.
The HTML builder decides what becomes an emitted asset.

## Main path

`src/projects/html_project/tracked_assets.rs`

Related paths:

- `src/projects/html_project/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/hir/`
- rendered path usage metadata carried from AST/HIR into builder-facing modules

## Frontend role

The frontend records rendered path usages as semantic facts.
It should not decide final asset emission policy.

Those facts can survive into builder-facing compiled modules along with doc fragments, warnings and other metadata.

## HTML builder role

The HTML builder owns:

- deciding which file paths become emitted assets
- choosing output paths relative to the final page route
- reporting asset warnings and conflicts
- returning asset bytes as ordinary `OutputFile` artifacts

Tracked assets are emitted through the same build-system output path as other artifacts.
They should not be copied directly by a lowerer.

## Route-relative paths

Asset output paths are chosen relative to the final page route.
That keeps generated HTML and emitted file layout consistent across pages.

The builder has the route context.
The frontend doesn't.

## Warnings and conflicts

Asset warnings and conflicts are builder policy.
They should be reported with structured diagnostics or warnings where the builder can point to useful source/rendered path context.

Don't hide missing or conflicting assets inside generic filesystem errors when the user wrote a path the builder can report.

## Common mistakes

- Treating asset copying as frontend behaviour.
- Emitting tracked assets outside the `OutputFile` path.
- Deciding route-relative output paths before the HTML builder knows the page route.
- Losing rendered path source context before asset warnings are produced.
- Letting stale emitted assets survive because the output writer wasn't given a cleanup policy.

